{"id":"ev_cb12bc0cf7b3400b","runId":"run_256","type":"delegation","at":1782518533722,"data":{"workItemId":"wi_86186026437f420d","atom":0,"task":"Atom 0 of ticket 0071 — fix the runner ORCHESTRATION DEADLOCK that made Bob loop with the runner in run_255 (the headline of ticket 0071). DAEMON/RUNNER CORE only. Do NOT touch packages/ui, the daemon routes, or any product feature code in this atom.\n\nROOT CAUSE (verified from run_255 events.jsonl): a non-loop (prose) atom has NO bounded no-progress cap. In packages/core/src/runner/monitor.ts the observation loop only returns from runMonitor on: 'done' (done-sentinel), 'blocked' (blocker marker), 'dead' (builder died), 'timeout' (now() >= deadline), or the loop-*-cap reasons — and for a NON-LOOP atom the only deadline is the builder turn timeout HEADLESS_BUILDER_TURN_TIMEOUT_MS = 14,400,000 ms (4 hours). So when the headless builder keeps producing output and getting re-nudged but never prints a done/blocker marker and never actually advances the work (run_255: a directive contradiction — pnpm typecheck required two test fixtures that directive-1 forbade), the atom does not terminate for up to 4 hours. Because the runner is parked inside executeAgentStep for the active atom, it never reads the NEXT directive Oscar wrote (directive-2 expanding scope) — Deb's nudges show 'directive-2.json exists ... but the status feed still lists only directive-1.json as delivered and Bob is still looping.' Only Deb's teardown broke it; run ended status=stopped, committedShas=[] (nothing shipped). Loop atoms are bounded by loop.maxIterations; prose atoms have no equivalent — that is the gap.\n\nFIX (root cause, minimal): give non-loop atoms a bounded NO-PROGRESS cap so a stuck builder terminates promptly as a quarantined/blocked atom and control returns to Oscar to re-scope via the next directive — exactly the recovery Oscar was reaching for with directive-2. Reuse the EXISTING loop-cap machinery; do not invent a parallel path.\n\nImplementation requirements:\n1. In monitor.ts add a bounded cap for non-loop atoms based on the number of NUDGES sent (each nudge drives a fresh builder turn; run_255 sent 19). When a non-loop atom (opts.loop === undefined) reaches a max-nudge bound WITHOUT reaching 'done' or 'blocked', return a NEW MonitorOutcomeReason (e.g. 'stall-cap'). Add the reason to the MonitorOutcomeReason union. Make the bound a single named constant with a sane default (pick a value in the 6–10 nudge range — well above normal need, well below 19) and document why. Count only nudges actually sent (respect the existing rate-limit), and never apply this cap to loop atoms (they keep using maxIterations/wallClockMs).\n2. In packages/core/src/runner/agent-step.ts, handle the new 'stall-cap' reason the SAME way as 'loop-iteration-cap'/'loop-wall-clock-cap': record an event (no silent cap — emit something like 'stall-capped' with the atom index and nudge count), quarantine the atom via quarantineAtom (nothing committed), and return { kind: 'blocked', outcomeLine } with a clear one-line outcome so the runner hands Oscar the next-or-wrap dispatch and consumes Oscar's next directive. Trace the existing cappedLoop/quarantine flow and mirror it.\n3. No silent truncation: the stall-cap MUST emit a run event and a log line naming the atom and the nudge count.\n\nACCEPTANCE (add a test that FAILS before your change and passes after):\n- A new test in the appropriate core test file (alongside the existing monitor/agent-step tests — find where runMonitor and loop caps are tested) reproduces run_255: a NON-LOOP atom whose builder never prints the done sentinel or a blocker marker and never makes the work pass. Assert runMonitor returns reason 'stall-cap' after the bounded number of nudges, NOT after the 4-hour timeout, and that it does so without a blocker marker. If practical at the agent-step layer, also assert the atom is quarantined and the step returns kind:'blocked' so the loop advances to the next directive.\n- Existing behavior preserved: 'done' (done-sentinel), 'blocked' (blocker marker), 'dead', 'timeout', and BOTH loop caps still work exactly as before; loop atoms are unaffected by the new cap; the nudge rate-limit is unchanged.\n\nMUST NOT BREAK / DO NOT: do not weaken or delete any existing monitor/agent-step/blocker test; do not change the blocker-marker semantics or the loop-cap thresholds; do not touch packages/ui or daemon routes; do not change HEADLESS_BUILDER_TURN_TIMEOUT_MS. Keep the change inside the runner core.\n\nVERIFY LOCALLY before printing your completion marker: run `pnpm --filter @cocoder/core typecheck` (or the repo's typecheck) AND the core test suite covering monitor/agent-step, and paste the real exit codes + the new test name. Report the exact files changed."}}
